# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: molecular-modeling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] In protein chemistry, **conformational ensembles**, also known as **structural ensembles**, are models describing the structure of intrinsically unstructured proteins.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] Such proteins are flexible in nature and cannot be described by a single structural representation.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] The techniques of ensemble calculation are relatively new on the field of structural biology, and are still facing certain limitations that need to be addressed before it will become comparable to classical structural description methods such as biological macromolecular crystallography.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] Ensembles are models consisting of a set of conformations that describe the structure of a flexible protein.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] Even though the degree of conformational freedom is extremely high, flexible/disordered protein generally differ from fully random coil structures.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] The main purpose of these models is to gain insights regarding the function of the flexible protein, extending the structure-function paradigm from folded proteins to intrinsically disordered proteins.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] The calculation of ensembles rely on experimental measurements, mostly by Neutron spin echo spectroscopy, Nuclear Magnetic Resonance spectroscopy and Small-angle X-ray scattering.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] These measurements yield structural information.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] The structure of disordered proteins may be approximated by running constrained molecular dynamics (MD) simulations where the conformational sampling is being influenced by experimentally derived constraints.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] Another approach uses selection algorithms such as ENSEMBLE and ASTEROIDS.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] Calculation procedures first generate a pool of random conformers (initial pool) so that they sufficiently sample the conformation space.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] The selection algorithms start by choosing a smaller set of conformers (an ensemble) from the initial pool.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] Experimental parameters (NMR/SAXS) are calculated (usually by some theoretical prediction methods) for each conformer of chosen ensemble and averaged over ensemble.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] The difference between these calculated parameters and true experimental parameters is used to make an error function and the algorithm selects the final ensemble so that the error function is minimised.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] The determination of a structural ensemble for an IDP from NMR/SAXS experimental parameters involves generation of structures that agree with the parameters and their respective weights in the ensemble.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] Usually, the available experimental data is less compared to the number of variables required to determine making it an under-determined system.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] Due to this reason, several structurally very different ensembles may describe the experimental data equally well, and currently there are no exact methods to discriminate between ensembles of equally good fit.
[src:molecular-modeling/conformational-ensemble] This problem has to be solved either by bringing in more experimental data or by improving the prediction methods by introducing rigorous computational methods.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] In the context of chemistry, molecular physics, physical chemistry, and molecular modelling, a **force field** is a computational model that is used to describe the forces between atoms (or collections of atoms) within molecules or between molecules as well as in crystals.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Force fields are a variety of interatomic potentials.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] More precisely, the force field refers to the functional form and parameter sets used to calculate the potential energy of a system on the atomistic level.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Force fields are usually used in molecular dynamics or Monte Carlo simulations.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The parameters for a chosen energy function may be derived from classical laboratory experiment data, calculations in quantum mechanics, or both.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Force fields utilize the same concept as force fields in classical physics, with the main difference being that the force field parameters in chemistry describe the energy landscape on the atomistic level.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] From a force field, the acting forces on every particle are derived as a gradient of the potential energy with respect to the particle coordinates.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] A large number of different force field types exist today (e.g. for organic molecules, ions, polymers, minerals, and metals).
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Depending on the material, different functional forms are usually chosen for the force fields since different types of atomistic interactions dominate the material behavior.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] There are various criteria that can be used for categorizing force field parametrization strategies.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] An important differentiation is 'component-specific' and 'transferable'.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] For a component-specific parametrization, the considered force field is developed solely for describing a single given substance (e.g. water).
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] For a transferable force field, all or some parameters are designed as building blocks and become transferable/ applicable for different substances (e.g. methyl groups in alkane transferable force fields).
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] *Coarse-grained* potentials, which are often used in long-time simulations of macromolecules such as proteins, nucleic acids, and multi-component complexes, sacrifice chemical details for higher computing efficiency.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The bond and angle terms are usually modeled by quadratic energy functions that do not allow bond breaking.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] A more realistic description of a covalent bond at higher stretching is provided by the more expensive Morse potential.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The functional form for dihedral energy is variable from one force field to another.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Additionally, "improper torsional" terms may be added to enforce the planarity of aromatic rings and other conjugated systems, and "cross-terms" that describe the coupling of different internal variables, such as angles and bond lengths.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Some force fields also include explicit terms for hydrogen bonds.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The nonbonded terms are computationally most intensive.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] A popular choice is to limit interactions to pairwise energies.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The van der Waals term is usually computed with a Lennard-Jones potential or the Mie potential and the electrostatic term with Coulomb's law.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] However, both can be buffered or scaled by a constant factor to account for electronic polarizability.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] A large number of force fields based on this or similar energy expressions have been proposed in the past decades for modeling different types of materials such as molecular substances, metals, glasses etc. - see below for a comprehensive list of force fields.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The term $l_{0,ij}$ is at times differently defined or taken at different thermodynamic conditions.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The bond stretching constant $k_{ij}$ can be determined from the experimental infrared spectrum, Raman spectrum, or high-level quantum-mechanical calculations.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The constant $k_{ij}$ determines vibrational frequencies in molecular dynamics simulations.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The stronger the bond is between atoms, the higher is the value of the force constant, and the higher the wavenumber (energy) in the IR/Raman spectrum.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Though the formula of Hooke's law provides a reasonable level of accuracy at bond lengths near the equilibrium distance, it is less accurate as one moves away.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] In order to model the Morse curve better, one could employ cubic and higher powers.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] However, for most practical applications these differences are negligible, and inaccuracies in predictions of bond lengths are on the order of the thousandth of an angstrom, which is also the limit of reliability for common force fields.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] A Morse potential can be employed instead to enable bond breaking and higher accuracy, even though it is less efficient to compute.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] For reactive force fields, bond breaking and bond orders are additionally considered.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] where $k_{i}^{\text{angle}}$ is the force constant, $\theta _{i}$ the angle between three atoms and $\theta _{0}$ the equilibrium angle.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] where $k_{i}^{\text{dihedral}}$ is the force constant, $\phi _{i}$ the dihedral angle, $\delta _{i}$ the phase and n defines the number of minima or maxima between 0 and $2\pi$ .
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Dihedral terms admit a range of mathematical representations, as illustrated by the multiple dihedral functional forms provided in OpenMM’s standard forces.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Electrostatic interactions are represented by a Coulomb energy, which utilizes atomic charges $q_{i}$ to represent chemical bonding ranging from covalent to polar covalent and ionic bonding.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The typical formula is the Coulomb law: $E_{\text{Coulomb}}={\frac {1}{4\pi \varepsilon _{0}}}{\frac {q_{i}q_{j}}{r_{ij}}},$ where $r_{ij}$ is the distance between two atoms i and j .
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The total Coulomb energy is a sum over all pairwise combinations of atoms and usually excludes 1, 2 bonded atoms, 1, 3 bonded atoms, as well as 1, 4 bonded atoms.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Atomic charges can make dominant contributions to the potential energy, especially for polar molecules and ionic compounds, and are critical to simulate the geometry, interaction energy, and the reactivity.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The assignment of charges usually uses some heuristic approach, with different possible solutions.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Historically the electrostatic potential (ESP) has been used to determine partial charges with the Merz-Kollman method being one of the first.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Other methods uses population based analysis schemes of wavefunctions like the Mulliken or Löwdin population analysis.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Another method to derive partial charges are charge equilibration methods like EEM, SQE or ACKS2.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The idea is to assign geometry-dependent charges by letting electronegativity differences drive charge flow between atoms until a self-consistent minimum of the electrostatic energy is reached.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Atomistic interactions in crystal systems significantly deviate from those in molecular systems, e.g. of organic molecules.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] For crystal systems, particularly multi-body interactions, these interactions are important and cannot be neglected if a high accuracy of the force field is the aim.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] For crystal systems with covalent bonding, bond order potentials are usually used, e.g.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] For metal systems, usually embedded atom potentials are used.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Additionally, Drude model potentials have been developed, which describe a form of attachment of electrons to nuclei.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] In addition to the functional form of the potentials, a force fields consists of the parameters of these functions.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Together, they specify the interactions on the atomistic level.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The parametrization, i.e. determining of the parameter values, is crucial for the accuracy and reliability of the force field.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Different parametrization procedures have been developed for the parametrization of different substances, e.g. metals, ions, and molecules.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] For different material types, usually different parametrization strategies are used.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] In general, two main types can be distinguished for the parametrization, either using data/ information from the atomistic level, e.g. from quantum mechanical calculations or spectroscopic data, or using data from macroscopic properties, e.g. the hardness or compressibility of a given material.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Often a combination of these routes is used.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Hence, one way or the other, the force field parameters are always determined in an empirical way.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Nevertheless, the term 'empirical' is often used in the context of force field parameters when macroscopic material property data was used for the fitting.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Experimental data (microscopic and macroscopic) included for the fit, for example, the enthalpy of vaporization, enthalpy of sublimation, dipole moments, and various spectroscopic properties such as vibrational frequencies.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Often, for molecular systems, quantum mechanical calculations in the gas phase are used for parametrizing intramolecular interactions and parametrizing intermolecular dispersive interactions by using macroscopic properties such as liquid densities.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The assignment of atomic charges often follows quantum mechanical protocols with some heuristics, which can lead to significant deviation in representing specific properties.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] A large number of workflows and parametrization procedures have been employed in the past decades using different data and optimization strategies for determining the force field parameters.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] They differ significantly, which is also due to different focuses of different developments.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The parameters for molecular simulations of biological macromolecules such as proteins, DNA, and RNA were often derived/transferred from observations for small organic molecules, which are more accessible for experimental studies and quantum calculations.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Atom types are defined for different elements as well as for the same elements in sufficiently different chemical environments.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] For example, oxygen atoms in water and an oxygen atoms in a carbonyl functional group are classified as different force field types.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Typical molecular force field parameter sets include values for atomic mass, atomic charge, Lennard-Jones parameters for every atom type, as well as equilibrium values of bond lengths, bond angles, and dihedral angles.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The bonded terms refer to pairs, triplets, and quadruplets of bonded atoms, and include values for the effective spring constant for each potential.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Efforts to provide open source codes and methods include openMM and openMD.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The use of semi-automation or full automation, without input from chemical knowledge, is likely to increase inconsistencies at the level of atomic charges, for the assignment of remaining parameters, and likely to dilute the interpretability and performance of parameters.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] A open-source software to derive parameters for different potential function is the Alexandria Chemistry Toolkit (ACT) which was published in 2025.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] It can generate and optimize physics-based force fields from scratch by machine learning.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Atom and bond parameters are considered genes of a genome, where force field accuracy is tied to the fitness of the genome.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Using a genetic algorithm (GA) and a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) algorithm, it can perform chromosomal crossovers and induce point mutations for global and local improvements closely resembling actual evolutionary operators.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Force field parameters are trained on quantum chemical energies, such as Symmetry-Adapted perturbation theory (SAPT) for non-covalent dimer interaction energies and Second-Order Møller-Plesset Perturbation Theory (MP2) scans for intramolecular energies.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] A large number of force fields has been published in the past decades - mostly in scientific publications.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] In recent years, some databases have attempted to collect, categorize and make force fields digitally available.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Therein, different databases focus on different types of force fields.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] For example, the openKim database focuses on interatomic functions describing the individual interactions between specific elements.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The TraPPE database focuses on transferable force fields of organic molecules (developed by the Siepmann group).
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The MolMod database focuses on molecular and ionic force fields (both component-specific and transferable).
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Functional forms and parameter sets have been defined by the developers of interatomic potentials and feature variable degrees of self-consistency and transferability.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] When functional forms of the potential terms vary or are mixed, the parameters from one interatomic potential function can typically not be used together with another interatomic potential function.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] In some cases, modifications can be made with minor effort, for example, between 9-6 Lennard-Jones potentials to 12-6 Lennard-Jones potentials.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Transfers from Buckingham potentials to harmonic potentials, or from Embedded Atom Models to harmonic potentials, on the contrary, would require many additional assumptions and may not be possible.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] In many cases, force fields can be straight forwardly combined.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Yet, often, additional specifications and assumptions are required.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] All interatomic potentials are based on approximations and experimental data, therefore often termed *empirical*.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The performance varies from higher accuracy than density functional theory (DFT) calculations, with access to million times larger systems and time scales, to random guesses depending on the force field.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The use of accurate representations of chemical bonding, combined with reproducible experimental data and validation, can lead to lasting interatomic potentials of high quality with much fewer parameters and assumptions in comparison to DFT-level quantum methods.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Possible limitations include atomic charges, also called point charges.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Most force fields rely on point charges to reproduce the electrostatic potential around molecules, which works less well for anisotropic charge distributions.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Electronic polarization of the environment may be better included by using *polarizable force fields* or using a macroscopic dielectric constant.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] However, application of one value of dielectric constant is a coarse approximation in the highly heterogeneous environments of proteins, biological membranes, minerals, or electrolytes.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] All types of van der Waals forces are also strongly environment-dependent because these forces originate from interactions of induced and "instantaneous" dipoles (see Intermolecular force).
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The original Fritz London theory of these forces applies only in a vacuum.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] A more general theory of van der Waals forces in condensed media was developed by A.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] McLachlan in 1963 and included the original London's approach as a special case.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The McLachlan theory predicts that van der Waals attractions in media are weaker than in vacuum and follow the *like dissolves like* rule, which means that different types of atoms interact more weakly than identical types of atoms.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] This is in contrast to *combinatorial rules* or Slater-Kirkwood equation applied for development of the classical force fields.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The *combinatorial rules* state that the interaction energy of two dissimilar atoms (e.g., C...N) is an average of the interaction energies of corresponding identical atom pairs (i.e., C...C and N...N).
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] According to McLachlan's theory, the interactions of particles in media can even be fully repulsive, as observed for liquid helium, however, the lack of vaporization and presence of a freezing point contradicts a theory of purely repulsive interactions.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Measurements of attractive forces between different materials (Hamaker constant) have been explained by Jacob Israelachvili.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] For example, "*the interaction between hydrocarbons across water is about 10% of that across vacuum*".
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Such effects are represented in molecular dynamics through pairwise interactions that are spatially more dense in the condensed phase relative to the gas phase and reproduced once the parameters for all phases are validated to reproduce chemical bonding, density, and cohesive/surface energy.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Limitations have been strongly felt in protein structure refinement.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The major underlying challenge is the huge conformation space of polymeric molecules, which grows beyond current computational feasibility when containing more than ~20 monomers.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Participants in Critical Assessment of protein Structure Prediction (CASP) did not try to refine their models to avoid "*a central embarrassment of molecular mechanics, namely that energy minimization or molecular dynamics generally leads to a model that is less like the experimental structure*".
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Force fields have been applied successfully for protein structure refinement in different X-ray crystallography and NMR spectroscopy applications, especially using program XPLOR.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] However, the refinement is driven mainly by a set of experimental constraints and the interatomic potentials serve mainly to remove interatomic hindrances.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The results of calculations were practically the same with rigid sphere potentials implemented in program DYANA (calculations from NMR data), or with programs for crystallographic refinement that use no energy functions at all.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] These shortcomings are related to interatomic potentials and to the inability to sample the conformation space of large molecules effectively.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Thereby also the development of parameters to tackle such large-scale problems requires new approaches.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] A specific problem area is homology modeling of proteins.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Meanwhile, alternative empirical scoring functions have been developed for ligand docking, protein folding, homology model refinement, computational protein design, and modeling of proteins in membranes.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] It was also argued that some protein force fields operate with energies that are irrelevant to protein folding or ligand binding.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The parameters of proteins force fields reproduce the enthalpy of sublimation, i.e., energy of evaporation of molecular crystals.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] However, protein folding and ligand binding are thermodynamically closer to crystallization, or liquid-solid transitions as these processes represent *freezing* of mobile molecules in condensed media.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Thus, free energy changes during protein folding or ligand binding are expected to represent a combination of an energy similar to heat of fusion (energy absorbed during melting of molecular crystals), a conformational entropy contribution, and solvation free energy.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The heat of fusion is significantly smaller than enthalpy of sublimation.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Hence, the potentials describing protein folding or ligand binding need more consistent parameterization protocols, e.g., as described for IFF.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The depths of modified Lennard-Jones potentials derived from protein engineering data were also smaller than in typical potential parameters and followed the *like dissolves like* rule, as predicted by McLachlan theory.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Several force fields explicitly capture polarizability, where a particle's effective charge can be influenced by electrostatic interactions with its neighbors.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Core-shell models are common, which consist of a positively charged core particle, representing the polarizable atom, and a negatively charged particle attached to the core atom through a spring-like harmonic oscillator potential.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Recent examples include polarizable models with virtual electrons that reproduce image charges in metals and polarizable biomolecular force fields.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] The set of parameters used to model water or aqueous solutions (basically a force field for water) is called a water model.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Many water models have been proposed; some examples are TIP3P, TIP4P, SPC, flexible simple point charge water model (flexible SPC), ST2, and mW.
[src:molecular-modeling/force-field-chemistry] Other solvents and methods of solvent representation are also applied within computational chemistry and physics; these are termed solvent models.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] In physical chemistry and classical mechanics, **molecular mechanics** is a computational method used to model molecular systems.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] The Born–Oppenheimer approximation is assumed valid and the potential energy of all systems is calculated as a function of the nuclear coordinates using force fields.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Molecular mechanics can be used to study molecule systems ranging in size and complexity from small to large biological systems or material assemblies with many thousands to millions of atoms.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] For example, many simulations have historically used a *united-atom* representation in which each terminal methyl group or intermediate methylene unit was considered one particle, and large protein systems are commonly simulated using a *bead* model that assigns two to four particles per amino acid.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] The following functional abstraction, termed an interatomic potential function or force field in chemistry, calculates the molecular system's potential energy (E) in a given conformation as a sum of individual energy terms.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] The exact functional form of the potential function, or force field, depends on the particular simulation program being used.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Generally the bond and angle terms are modeled as harmonic potentials centered around equilibrium bond-length values derived from experiment or theoretical calculations of electronic structure performed with software which does *ab-initio* type calculations such as Gaussian.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] For accurate reproduction of vibrational spectra, the Morse potential can be used instead, at computational cost.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] The dihedral or torsional terms typically have multiple minima and thus cannot be modeled as harmonic oscillators, though their specific functional form varies with the implementation.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] This class of terms may include *improper* dihedral terms, which function as correction factors for out-of-plane deviations (for example, they can be used to keep benzene rings planar, or correct geometry and chirality of tetrahedral atoms in a united-atom representation).
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] The non-bonded terms are much more computationally costly to calculate in full, since a typical atom is bonded to only a few of its neighbors, but interacts with every other atom in the molecule.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Fortunately the van der Waals term falls off rapidly.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] It is typically modeled using a *6–12 Lennard-Jones potential*, which means that attractive forces fall off with distance as *r*−6 and repulsive forces as *r*−12, where r represents the distance between two atoms.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] The repulsive part *r*−12 is however unphysical, because repulsion increases exponentially.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Description of van der Waals forces by the Lennard-Jones 6–12 potential introduces inaccuracies, which become significant at short distances.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Generally a cutoff radius is used to speed up the calculation so that atom pairs which distances are greater than the cutoff have a van der Waals interaction energy of zero.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] The electrostatic terms are notoriously difficult to calculate well because they do not fall off rapidly with distance, and long-range electrostatic interactions are often important features of the system under study (especially for proteins).
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] The basic functional form is the Coulomb potential, which only falls off as *r*−1.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] A variety of methods are used to address this problem, the simplest being a cutoff radius similar to that used for the van der Waals terms.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] However, this introduces a sharp discontinuity between atoms inside and atoms outside the radius.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Switching or scaling functions that modulate the apparent electrostatic energy are somewhat more accurate methods that multiply the calculated energy by a smoothly varying scaling factor from 0 to 1 at the outer and inner cutoff radii.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Other more sophisticated but computationally intensive methods are particle mesh Ewald (PME) and the multipole algorithm.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] In addition to the functional form of each energy term, a useful energy function must be assigned parameters for force constants, van der Waals multipliers, and other constant terms.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] These terms, together with the equilibrium bond, angle, and dihedral values, partial charge values, atomic masses and radii, and energy function definitions, are collectively termed a force field.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Parameterization is typically done through agreement with experimental values and theoretical calculations results.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Allinger's force field in the last MM4 version calculate for hydrocarbons heats of formation with a RMS error of 0.35 kcal/mol, vibrational spectra with a RMS error of 24 cm−1, rotational barriers with a RMS error of 2.2°, C−C bond lengths within 0.004 Å and C−C−C angles within 1°.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Later MM4 versions cover also compounds with heteroatoms such as aliphatic amines.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Each force field is parameterized to be internally consistent, but the parameters are generally not transferable from one force field to another.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] The main use of molecular mechanics is in the field of molecular dynamics.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] This uses the force field to calculate the forces acting on each particle and a suitable integrator to model the dynamics of the particles and predict trajectories.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Given enough sampling and subject to the ergodic hypothesis, molecular dynamics trajectories can be used to estimate thermodynamic parameters of a system or probe kinetic properties, such as reaction rates and mechanisms.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Molecular mechanics is also used within QM/MM, which allows study of proteins and enzyme kinetics.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] The system is divided into two regions—one of which is treated with quantum mechanics (QM) allowing breaking and formation of bonds and the rest of the protein is modeled using molecular mechanics (MM).
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] MM alone does not allow the study of mechanisms of enzymes, which QM allows.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] QM also produces more exact energy calculation of the system although it is much more computationally expensive.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Another application of molecular mechanics is energy minimization, whereby the force field is used as an optimization criterion.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] This method uses an appropriate algorithm (e.g. steepest descent) to find the molecular structure of a local energy minimum.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] These minima correspond to stable conformers of the molecule (in the chosen force field) and molecular motion can be modelled as vibrations around and interconversions between these stable conformers.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] It is thus common to find local energy minimization methods combined with global energy optimization, to find the global energy minimum (and other low energy states).
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] At finite temperature, the molecule spends most of its time in these low-lying states, which thus dominate the molecular properties.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Global optimization can be accomplished using simulated annealing, the Metropolis algorithm and other Monte Carlo methods, or using different deterministic methods of discrete or continuous optimization.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] While the force field represents only the enthalpic component of free energy (and only this component is included during energy minimization), it is possible to include the entropic component through the use of additional methods, such as normal mode analysis.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Molecular mechanics potential energy functions have been used to calculate binding constants, protein folding kinetics, protonation equilibria, active site coordinates, and to design binding sites.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] In molecular mechanics, several ways exist to define the environment surrounding a molecule or molecules of interest.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] A system can be simulated in vacuum (termed a gas-phase simulation) with no surrounding environment, but this is usually undesirable because it introduces artifacts in the molecular geometry, especially in charged molecules.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] Surface charges that would ordinarily interact with solvent molecules instead interact with each other, producing molecular conformations that are unlikely to be present in any other environment.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] The most accurate way to solvate a system is to place explicit water molecules in the simulation box with the molecules of interest and treat the water molecules as interacting particles like those in the other molecule(s).
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] A variety of water models exist with increasing levels of complexity, representing water as a simple hard sphere (a united-atom model), as three separate particles with fixed bond angle, or even as four or five separate interaction centers to account for unpaired electrons on the oxygen atom.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] As water models grow more complex, related simulations grow more computationally intensive.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] A compromise method has been found in implicit solvation, which replaces the explicitly represented water molecules with a mathematical expression that reproduces the average behavior of water molecules (or other solvents such as lipids).
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-mechanics] This is a limited list; many more packages are available.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Molecular mechanics is one aspect of molecular modelling, as it involves the use of classical mechanics (Newtonian mechanics) to describe the physical basis behind the models.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Molecular models typically describe atoms (nucleus and electrons collectively) as point charges with an associated mass.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] The interactions between neighbouring atoms are described by spring-like interactions (representing chemical bonds) and Van der Waals forces.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] The Lennard-Jones potential is commonly used to describe the latter.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] The electrostatic interactions are computed based on Coulomb's law.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Atoms are assigned coordinates in Cartesian space or in internal coordinates, and can also be assigned velocities in dynamical simulations.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] The atomic velocities are related to the temperature of the system, a macroscopic quantity.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] The collective mathematical expression is termed a potential function and is related to the system internal energy (U), a thermodynamic quantity equal to the sum of potential and kinetic energies.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Methods which minimize the potential energy are termed energy minimization methods (e.g., steepest descent and conjugate gradient), while methods that model the behaviour of the system with propagation of time are termed molecular dynamics.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] The set of parameters consisting of equilibrium bond lengths, bond angles, partial charge values, force constants and van der Waals parameters are collectively termed a force field.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Different implementations of molecular mechanics use different mathematical expressions and different parameters for the potential function.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] The common force fields in use today have been developed by using chemical theory, experimental reference data, and high level quantum calculations.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] The method, termed energy minimization, is used to find positions of zero gradient for all atoms, in other words, a local energy minimum.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Lower energy states are more stable and are commonly investigated because of their role in chemical and biological processes.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] A molecular dynamics simulation, on the other hand, computes the behaviour of a system as a function of time.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] It involves solving Newton's laws of motion, principally the second law, $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a}$ .
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Integration of Newton's laws of motion, using different integration algorithms, leads to atomic trajectories in space and time.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] The force on an atom is defined as the negative gradient of the potential energy function.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] The energy minimization method is useful to obtain a static picture for comparing between states of similar systems, while molecular dynamics provides information about the dynamic processes with the intrinsic inclusion of temperature effects.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Molecules can be modelled either in vacuum, or in the presence of a solvent such as water.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Simulations of systems in vacuum are referred to as *gas-phase* simulations, while those that include the presence of solvent molecules are referred to as *explicit solvent* simulations.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] In another type of simulation, the effect of solvent is estimated using an empirical mathematical expression; these are termed *implicit solvation* simulations.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Most force fields are distance-dependent, making the most convenient expression for these Cartesian coordinates.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Yet the comparatively rigid nature of bonds which occur between specific atoms, and in essence, defines what is meant by the designation *molecule*, make an internal coordinate system the most logical representation.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] In some fields the IC representation (bond length, angle between bonds, and twist angle of the bond as shown in the figure) is termed the Z-matrix or torsion angle representation.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Thus, it is very common for computational optimizing programs to flip back and forth between representations during their iterations.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] This can dominate the calculation time of the potential itself and in long chain molecules introduce cumulative numerical inaccuracy.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] While all conversion algorithms produce mathematically identical results, they differ in speed and numerical accuracy.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Currently, the fastest and most accurate torsion to Cartesian conversion is the Natural Extension Reference Frame (NERF) method.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] Molecular modelling methods are used routinely to investigate the structure, dynamics, surface properties, and thermodynamics of inorganic, biological, and polymeric systems.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] A large number of molecular models of force field are today readily available in databases.
[src:molecular-modeling/molecular-modelling] The types of biological activity that have been investigated using molecular modelling include protein folding, enzyme catalysis, protein stability, conformational changes associated with biomolecular function, and molecular recognition of proteins, DNA, and membrane complexes.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] A **potential energy surface** (**PES**) or **energy landscape** describes the energy of a system, especially a collection of atoms, in terms of certain parameters, normally the positions of the atoms.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] The surface might define the energy as a function of one or more coordinates; if there is only one coordinate, the surface is called a *potential energy curve* or energy profile.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] An example is the Morse/Long-range potential.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] It is helpful to use the analogy of a landscape: for a system with two degrees of freedom (e.g. two bond lengths), the value of the energy (analogy: the height of the land) is a function of two bond lengths (analogy: the coordinates of the position on the ground).
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] The PES concept finds application in fields such as physics, chemistry and biochemistry, especially in the theoretical sub-branches of these subjects.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] It can be used to theoretically explore properties of structures composed of atoms, for example, finding the minimum energy shape of a molecule or computing the rates of a chemical reaction.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] It can be used to describe all possible conformations of a molecular entity, or the spatial positions of interacting molecules in a system, or parameters and their corresponding energy levels, typically Gibbs free energy.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] Geometrically, the energy landscape is the graph of the energy function across the configuration space of the system.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] The term is also used more generally in geometric perspectives to mathematical optimization, when the domain of the loss function is the parameter space of some system.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] The geometry of a set of atoms can be described by a vector, **r**, whose elements represent the atom positions.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] The vector **r** could be the set of the Cartesian coordinates of the atoms, or could also be a set of inter-atomic distances and angles.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] Given **r**, the energy as a function of the positions, *E*(**r**), is the value of *E*(**r**) for all **r** of interest.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] Using the landscape analogy from the introduction, *E* gives the height on the "energy landscape" so that the concept of a potential energy *surface* arises.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] To study a chemical reaction using the PES as a function of atomic positions, it is necessary to calculate the energy for every atomic arrangement of interest.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] Methods of calculating the energy of a particular atomic arrangement of atoms are well described in the computational chemistry article, and the emphasis here will be on finding approximations of *E*(**r**) to yield fine-grained energy-position information.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] For very simple chemical systems or when simplifying approximations are made about inter-atomic interactions, it is sometimes possible to use an analytically derived expression for the energy as a function of the atomic positions.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] An example is the London-Eyring-Polanyi-Sato potential for the system H + H2 as a function of the three H-H distances.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] For more complicated systems, calculation of the energy of a particular arrangement of atoms is often too computationally expensive for large scale representations of the surface to be feasible.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] For these systems a possible approach is to calculate only a reduced set of points on the PES and then use a computationally cheaper interpolation method, for example Shepard interpolation, to fill in the gaps.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] A PES is a conceptual tool for aiding the analysis of molecular geometry and chemical reaction dynamics.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] Once the necessary points are evaluated on a PES, the points can be classified according to the first and second derivatives of the energy with respect to position, which respectively are the gradient and the curvature.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] The term is useful when examining protein folding; while a protein can theoretically exist in a nearly infinite number of conformations along its energy landscape, in reality proteins fold (or "relax") into secondary and tertiary structures that possess the lowest possible free energy.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] The key concept in the energy landscape approach to protein folding is the *folding funnel* hypothesis.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] In catalysis, when designing new catalysts or refining existing ones, energy landscapes are considered to avoid low-energy or high-energy intermediates that could halt the reaction or demand excessive energy to reach the final products.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] In glassing models, the local minima of an energy landscape correspond to metastable low temperature states of a thermodynamic system.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] In machine learning, artificial neural networks may be analyzed using analogous approaches.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] For example, a neural network may be able to perfectly fit the training set, corresponding to a global minimum of zero loss, but overfitting the model ("learning the noise" or "memorizing the training set").
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] Understanding when this happens can be studied using the geometry of the corresponding energy landscape.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] Potential energy surfaces for chemical reactions can be classified as *attractive* or *repulsive* by comparing the extensions of the bond lengths in the activated complex relative to those of the reactants and products.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] For a reaction of type A + B—C → A—B + C, the bond length extension for the newly formed A—B bond is defined as R*AB = RAB − R0AB, where RAB is the A—B bond length in the transition state and R0AB in the product molecule.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] Similarly for the bond which is broken in the reaction, R*BC = RBC − R0BC, where R0BC refers to the reactant molecule.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] For exothermic reactions, a PES is classified as *attractive* (or *early-downhill*) if R*AB > R*BC, so that the transition state is reached while the reactants are approaching each other.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] After the transition state, the A—B bond length continues to decrease, so that much of the liberated reaction energy is converted into vibrational energy of the A—B bond.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] An example is the harpoon reaction K + Br2 → K—Br + Br, in which the initial long-range attraction of the reactants leads to an activated complex resembling K+•••Br−•••Br.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] The vibrationally excited populations of product molecules can be detected by infrared chemiluminescence.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] In contrast the PES for the reaction H + Cl2 → HCl + Cl is *repulsive* (or *late-downhill*) because R*HCl < R*ClCl and the transition state is reached when the products are separating.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] For this reaction in which the atom A (here H) is lighter than B and C, the reaction energy is released primarily as translational kinetic energy of the products.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] For a reaction such as F + H2 → HF + H in which atom A is heavier than B and C, there is *mixed* energy release, both vibrational and translational, even though the PES is repulsive.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] For endothermic reactions, the type of surface determines the type of energy which is most effective in bringing about reaction.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] Translational energy of the reactants is most effective at inducing reactions with an attractive surface, while vibrational excitation (to higher vibrational quantum number v) is more effective for reactions with a repulsive surface.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] As an example of the latter case, the reaction F + HCl(v=1) → Cl + HF is about five times faster than F + HCl(v=0) → Cl + HF for the same total energy of HCl.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] The concept of a potential energy surface for chemical reactions was first suggested by the French physicist René Marcelin in 1913.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] The first semi-empirical calculation of a potential energy surface was proposed for the H + H2 reaction by Henry Eyring and Michael Polanyi in 1931.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] Eyring used potential energy surfaces to calculate reaction rate constants in the transition state theory in 1935.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] Potential energy surfaces are commonly shown as three-dimensional graphs, but they can also be represented by two-dimensional graphs, in which the advancement of the reaction is plotted by the use of isoenergetic lines.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] The collinear system H + H2 is a simple reaction that allows a two-dimension PES to be plotted in an easy and understandable way.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] In this reaction, a hydrogen atom (H) reacts with a dihydrogen molecule (H2) by forming a new bond with one atom from the molecule, which in turn breaks the bond of the original molecule.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] This is symbolized as Ha + Hb–Hc → Ha–Hb + Hc.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] The progression of the reaction from reactants (H+H₂) to products (H-H-H), as well as the energy of the species that take part in the reaction, are well defined in the corresponding potential energy surface.
[src:molecular-modeling/potential-energy-surface] Energy profiles describe potential energy as a function of geometrical variables (PES in any dimension are independent of time and temperature).
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] In chemistry, the **Z-matrix** is a way to represent a system built of atoms.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] A Z-matrix is also known as an **internal coordinate representation**.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] However, it is convenient to write a Z-matrix in terms of bond lengths, angles, and dihedrals since this will preserve the actual bonding characteristics.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] The name arises because the Z-matrix assigns the second atom along the Z axis from the first atom, which is at the origin.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] While the transform is conceptually straightforward, algorithms of doing the conversion vary significantly in speed, numerical precision and parallelism.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] Back-conversion from Cartesian to torsion angles is simple trigonometry and has no risk of cumulative errors.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] They are used for creating input geometries for molecular systems in many molecular modelling and computational chemistry programs.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] A skillful choice of internal coordinates can make the interpretation of results straightforward.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] The Z-matrix representation is often preferred, because this allows symmetry to be enforced upon the molecule (or parts thereof) by setting certain angles as constant.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] The Z-matrix simply is a representation for placing atomic positions in a relative way with the obvious convenience that the vectors it uses easily correspond to bonds.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] A conceptual pitfall is to assume all bonds appear as a line in the Z-matrix which is not true.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] For example: in ringed molecules like benzene, a z-matrix will not include all six bonds in the ring, because all of the atoms are uniquely positioned after just 5 bonds making the 6th redundant.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] Reorienting the molecule leads to Cartesian coordinates that make the symmetry more obvious.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] This removes the bond length of 1.089 from the explicit parameters.
[src:molecular-modeling/z-matrix-chemistry] Only the 1.089000 value is not fixed by tetrahedral symmetry.
